00:53:13.820 --> 00:53:16.660
we tend to come in and offer
these sort of point solutions.

00:53:16.660 --> 00:53:18.960
And I'm sorry if this
question is a bit leading,

00:53:18.960 --> 00:53:21.400
but what is it that
a company like Google

00:53:21.400 --> 00:53:24.960
should be doing whenever
we're talking to our customers

00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:27.460
rather than just offering them
point solutions whenever they

00:53:27.460 --> 00:53:29.620
are trying to make a change,
a fundamental change,

00:53:29.620 --> 00:53:32.060
in their business and
how they approach things?

00:53:32.060 --> 00:53:34.420
SCOTT ANTHONY: So if you
look at that idea of tripling

00:53:34.420 --> 00:53:36.880
the amount of time you spend
with customers, if you know

00:53:36.880 --> 00:53:39.570
Innosight, you know Clayton
Christensen and his writings,

00:53:39.570 --> 00:53:41.890
you know one of the
big ideas we focus on

00:53:41.890 --> 00:53:43.870
is the customer's
job to be done.

00:53:43.870 --> 00:53:46.220
What is the problem
they're trying to solve?

00:53:46.220 --> 00:53:48.585
And in a B2B world,
it's pretty simple.

00:53:48.585 --> 00:53:49.870
Well, along said dimension.

00:53:49.870 --> 00:53:51.790
The business of
business is business.

00:53:51.790 --> 00:53:54.550
So what you always want to
do when you're in a service

00:53:54.550 --> 00:53:56.620
provider space, when
you're in a B2B space

00:53:56.620 --> 00:53:59.940
is understand the context in
which your customers operate

00:53:59.940 --> 00:54:03.220
and think not just about how
you deliver a cloud install

00:54:03.220 --> 00:54:05.816
or whatever, but what's
the business context

00:54:05.816 --> 00:54:06.940
in which they're operating.

00:54:06.940 --> 00:54:08.722
What are the challenges
they're facing?

00:54:08.722 --> 00:54:10.180
What are the other
things that need

00:54:10.180 --> 00:54:12.310
to happen for them to
increase their ability

00:54:12.310 --> 00:54:14.810
to be competitive,
to engage employees,

00:54:14.810 --> 00:54:16.160
et cetera, et cetera?

00:54:16.160 --> 00:54:18.460
So this mindset of
always asking yourself

00:54:18.460 --> 00:54:20.620
what actually is
the customer's job

00:54:20.620 --> 00:54:22.780
to be done and not
just the one who I'm

00:54:22.780 --> 00:54:25.480
having the conversation
with, not just the buyer,

00:54:25.480 --> 00:54:28.240
but what's the buyer-- what is
the circumstance in which they

00:54:28.240 --> 00:54:30.920
sit, and who are the other
influencers, et cetera,

00:54:30.920 --> 00:54:31.494
et cetera.

00:54:31.494 --> 00:54:33.910
That's, I think, the mindset
that you always need to have.

00:54:33.910 --> 00:54:35.890
And I think it's not
dissimilar to what

00:54:35.890 --> 00:54:38.450
we need to think about to be
good advisors to companies.

00:54:38.450 --> 00:54:40.810
So we might get hired
by an executive who

00:54:40.810 --> 00:54:43.060
says, I need to think about
this new growth business

00:54:43.060 --> 00:54:43.965
or whatever.

00:54:43.965 --> 00:54:45.340
But what they
actually need to do

00:54:45.340 --> 00:54:47.560
is have a story that they
can tell to a shareholder,

00:54:47.560 --> 00:54:49.529
or they might have a
board of directors member

00:54:49.529 --> 00:54:51.070
that's causing them
a lot of trouble,

00:54:51.070 --> 00:54:52.529
or they might have
a power struggle

00:54:52.529 --> 00:54:53.528
that they're trying to--

00:54:53.528 --> 00:54:54.130
whatever.

00:54:54.130 --> 00:54:56.350
We need to understand
that, because giving

00:54:56.350 --> 00:54:59.080
the right technical answer
to the question asked

00:54:59.080 --> 00:55:01.180
is typically insufficient
to ultimately

00:55:01.180 --> 00:55:03.190
have impact in your
line of business,

00:55:03.190 --> 00:55:04.889
in our line of business as well.

00:55:04.889 --> 00:55:06.430
AUDIENCE: I'll ask
two more questions

00:55:06.430 --> 00:55:08.620
that were submitted
as part of a survey

00:55:08.620 --> 00:55:11.320
that we provided earlier.

00:55:11.320 --> 00:55:15.880
One of them was, can I
start a business with $0?

00:55:15.880 --> 00:55:17.980
SCOTT ANTHONY: Yeah,
so the Plunify example

00:55:17.980 --> 00:55:19.400
is a perfect example of that.

00:55:19.400 --> 00:55:20.858
And if you looked
at the screen, it

00:55:20.858 --> 00:55:24.160
was the excited space of
cloud-accelerated chip design.

00:55:24.160 --> 00:55:26.552
I do not remember at all
what that is, but whatever.

00:55:26.552 --> 00:55:28.510
It was a business that
we started from nothing.

00:55:28.510 --> 00:55:29.634
And this is the norm today.

00:55:29.634 --> 00:55:31.840
A lot of businesses are
started for nothing.

00:55:31.840 --> 00:55:33.632
And of course, there
are lots of businesses

00:55:33.632 --> 00:55:35.256
that you could do as
an individual that

00:55:35.256 --> 00:55:36.670
require no capital investment.

00:55:36.670 --> 00:55:39.730
Starting a business for nothing
is actually quite trivial

00:55:39.730 --> 00:55:40.600
to do.

00:55:40.600 --> 00:55:43.525
Scaling it, on the other hand,
that still requires capital.

00:55:43.525 --> 00:55:47.290
And this, again, is one
of the great advantages

00:55:47.290 --> 00:55:48.870
a company like Google has.

00:55:48.870 --> 00:55:52.060
You have more capital
than probably any company

00:55:52.060 --> 00:55:53.630
in the Western world.

00:55:53.630 --> 00:55:55.720
So that gives you
advantages over startups

00:55:55.720 --> 00:55:58.900
that are scarce of capital and
have to fight fiercely and have

00:55:58.900 --> 00:56:00.490
to fight against
would-be competitors,

00:56:00.490 --> 00:56:01.671
et cetera, et cetera.

00:56:01.671 --> 00:56:03.670
You have the ability to
think and act at a scale

00:56:03.670 --> 00:56:05.530
that few other
organizations can follow.

00:56:05.530 --> 00:56:07.900
So yes, you can start
a business for nothing.

00:56:07.900 --> 00:56:10.730
But remember, so can
everybody else in the room.

00:56:10.730 --> 00:56:12.406
So if you've got
an idea, and you

00:56:12.406 --> 00:56:13.780
start to get some
early traction,

00:56:13.780 --> 00:56:15.940
then everybody else is
going to go and try and do

00:56:15.940 --> 00:56:16.970
the same thing.

00:56:16.970 --> 00:56:21.340
Whereas here, at Google, you've
got unique, hard-earned assets

00:56:21.340 --> 00:56:24.820
that you've built over your
20-plus-year history that are

00:56:24.820 --> 00:56:26.410
really difficult to replicate.

00:56:26.410 --> 00:56:29.120
And think about what you can
do with that as an advantage.

00:56:29.120 --> 00:56:32.290
It's that example or
the idea of having both.

00:56:32.290 --> 00:56:34.330
So you both have
the assets of scale

00:56:34.330 --> 00:56:35.841
and the entrepreneurial energy.

00:56:35.841 --> 00:56:37.840
When you bring the two
of those things together,

00:56:37.840 --> 00:56:40.085
it is a really
powerful combination.

00:56:40.085 --> 00:56:41.710
AUDIENCE: OK, and I
guess that takes me

00:56:41.710 --> 00:56:44.230
into one of the other
questions that was asked.

00:56:44.230 --> 00:56:46.960
For those of us then that
have made that choice

00:56:46.960 --> 00:56:50.000
to join a larger organization
and try to change the world,

00:56:50.000 --> 00:56:53.620
what can we do as individuals
to innovate inside

00:56:53.620 --> 00:56:55.410
of our own roles and companies?

00:56:55.410 --> 00:56:58.330
SCOTT ANTHONY: So the seven
things that I had on-- this

00:56:58.330 --> 00:57:01.840
is from-- the list of seven
things is a slightly modified

00:57:01.840 --> 00:57:04.510
version of something that I had
at the end of "The Little Black

00:57:04.510 --> 00:57:08.920
Book of Innovation" called
The Innovator's Pledge.

00:57:08.920 --> 00:57:11.890
Doing those things
repeatedly, spending more time

00:57:11.890 --> 00:57:14.290
with customers, spending
more time at the periphery,

00:57:14.290 --> 00:57:16.380
running experiments,
and so on, you

00:57:16.380 --> 00:57:18.460
don't have to be a
CEO or somebody who's

00:57:18.460 --> 00:57:20.500
got a big budget, who
runs a business, to do it.

00:57:20.500 --> 00:57:22.060
These are day-to-day
habits that you

00:57:22.060 --> 00:57:24.940
can bring into your own
individual behavior,

00:57:24.940 --> 00:57:27.056
to your team's
individual behavior.

00:57:27.056 --> 00:57:28.930
And the thing that I'd
ask you to think about

00:57:28.930 --> 00:57:31.600
if this is a struggle for your
team, group, or department,

00:57:31.600 --> 00:57:32.330
is why.

00:57:32.330 --> 00:57:33.940
What are the things,
the blockers,

00:57:33.940 --> 00:57:36.040
that are standing in
the way of success?

00:57:36.040 --> 00:57:38.380
Sometimes it's a norm
that needs to be changed.

00:57:38.380 --> 00:57:40.930
Sometimes it's a system
that needs to be changed.

00:57:40.930 --> 00:57:42.850
Sometimes it's you
as a leader, what

00:57:42.850 --> 00:57:44.920
you need to do differently
in order to role model

00:57:44.920 --> 00:57:46.520
a different behavior.

00:57:46.520 --> 00:57:48.790
But it all starts with
going and recognizing

00:57:48.790 --> 00:57:51.190
that to do something different
that creates value, which

00:57:51.190 --> 00:57:54.590
is how we define innovation,
there are a set of practices,

00:57:54.590 --> 00:57:57.279
there are a set of habits that
increase the odds of success.

00:57:57.279 --> 00:57:58.820
So we've just got
to do those things,

00:57:58.820 --> 00:58:00.010
and we've got to
do them repeatedly.

00:58:00.010 --> 00:58:02.410
And we have to enable other
people in our team, group,

00:58:02.410 --> 00:58:05.006
or department do
those things as well.

